The article is a statement from the Nuclear Security Summit in Seoul in March 2012. The participants of the summit reaffirm their commitment to the security of nuclear information and express the importance of preventing non-state actors from obtaining nuclear materials or disrupting information technology systems at nuclear facilities. They encourage states to develop and strengthen measures for the effective management of nuclear information, support capacity building projects, and enhance cyber security measures. The participants also commit to developing and strengthening national measures for the security of nuclear information, enhancing national security culture, engaging with scientific and academic communities, and collaborating with international organizations to achieve these goals. They outline specific actions to be taken, such as conducting national assurance exercises, implementing international guidance on computer security at nuclear facilities, and recognizing the role of industry in promoting best practices. The statement includes a list of the 31 countries that are parties to the statement.